g.text: 4.2 Block Matching
Block matching is an algorithm used in stereo vision to compute the
correspondence between pixels in two images taken from slightly different viewpoint
Correspondence ambiguity
illustrated-machine-learning.github.io
How to determine if two image points correspond?
1. Ideally, they need to look similar
2. A single pixel does not reveal the local structure (ambiguities)
3. Therefore, we should compare smaller regions
-> it makes it easier, but it doesn't entirely solve the problem
what does it mean?
Correspondence ambiguity
1. We take a scan line (because of the rectification!)
2. We query all patches along the line
3. We measure their similarity, aiming for a peak!
We do not need to search on the grey region.
The displacement goes to the left!
Similarity Metrics
Consider two KxK patches plattened to vectors
Takes a patch on the left image and normalizes it by
subtracting its mean and dividing by its variance. Then
computes the dot product with the normalized patch on
the right image
Note the '-d' for the second image.
Zero Normalized Cross Correlation (ZNCC)
Sum of Squared Differences (SSD)
Takes the left patch and the right patch. Then,
subtract both and compute the sum of squares.
